      "source": [
        "# Train-Test Split\n",
        "\n",
        "**This cell splits the data into the data the model will train and the data the model will test. 75 percent of the data is used to train the model and the other 25 percent is used to test the model**"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "background_save": true
        },
        "id": "G_r27PlYU5mQ"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "train_size = int(len(df_2d) * 0.75)\n",
        "test_size = len(df_2d) - train_size\n",
        "train, test = df_2d[:train_size], df_2d[train_size:]"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "yZ_iGaCNcKx9"
      },
      "source": [
        "# Preprocessing\n",
        "Data preprocessing is the first step in any data analysis or machine learning pipeline. It involves cleaning, transforming and organizing raw data to ensure it is accurate, consistent and ready for modeling."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "yoHdnXVdc1jr"
      },
      "source": [
        "**Robust Scaler**\n",
        "\n",
        "* Robust Scaler is the normalization\n",
        "method used since it does well with extreme values and outliers in datasets such as this one."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "background_save": true
        },
        "id": "C5viiIAXVdF4"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "robust_scaler = RobustScaler()\n",
        "scaled_train = robust_scaler.fit_transform(train)\n",
        "scaled_test = robust_scaler.transform(test)"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "yvHMt6Lfelx_"
      },
      "source": [
        "\n",
        "**Create Dataset Function**\n",
        "*  Stores the input sequences (features) and their corresponding target sequences,\n",
        "*   The loop runs from the beginning of the dataset up to len(dataset) - look_back.  because for each input sequence of length look_back, you need a target sequence of the same length that follows it.\n",
        "\n",
        "*   This structured format of input and target sequences is crucial for training sequence models like LSTMs, where the model learns to predict the next steps in a sequence based on the previous steps.\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "background_save": true
        },
        "id": "QOPxZb8IU9ii"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "def create_dataset(dataset, look_back):\n",
        "    X , y = [], []\n",
        "    for i in range(len(dataset)-look_back):\n",
        "        feature = dataset[i:i+look_back]\n",
        "        target = dataset[i+1:i+look_back+1]\n",
        "        X.append(feature)\n",
        "        y.append(target)\n",
        "    return np.array(X), np.array(y)"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "zUOr3ebMe-gw"
      },
      "source": [
        "Implementing the Create Dataset function\n",
        "\n",
        "*  A lookback value of 5 means that each input sequence for the model will consist of 5 data points, and the model will try to predict the next data point\n",
        "* We print the shape of the testing and training set to see what parameters are needed for the model\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "background_save": true,
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "43YJAhC_VBS0",
        "outputId": "3929a032-e511-42ef-e790-d662d23c978b"
      },
      "outputs": [
        {
          "name": "stdout",
          "output_type": "stream",
          "text": [
            "(64, 5, 1) (64, 5, 1)\n",
            "(18, 5, 1) (18, 5, 1)\n"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "source": [
        "look_back = 5\n",
        "X_train, y_train = create_dataset(scaled_train, look_back=look_back)\n",
        "X_test, y_test = create_dataset(scaled_test, look_back=look_back)\n",
        "print(X_train.shape, y_train.shape)\n",
        "print(X_test.shape, y_test.shape)"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "4mOWIfdIfdmu"
      },
      "source": [
        "# Building and Training the LSTM Model\n",
        "* Width variable is the number of time steps(look_back period) 5 and height is the number of features which is 1 (flows).\n",
        "* Next we initialize the sequential model which is a stack of layers\n",
        "\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "KDtakRdHgXvX"
      },
      "source": [
        "**Layers of the model**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "1.   The first later consists of an LSTM layer with 64 units wich are neurons for the model\n",
        "* Return sequences is set to false meaninf the LSTM layer will output a single for each input sequence.\n",
        "* Input_Shape specifies the shape of the input data\n",
        "2.  The second layer is a Dropout layer with the rate of 0.3. A dropout layer helps prevent the model from training to well not allowing it to adjust to new data by setting a fraction of input units to 0.\n",
        "3.  This adds a Dense (fully connected) layer with look_back units. This layer will output the predicted values.\n",
        "\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "cWQHjtWGiJ2f"
      },
      "source": [
        "**Compiling the Model**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "*   Compiling the model tells the model how it will learn and how it's performance will be measured\n",
        "*   The optimizer used is Adam with a learning rate of 0.01\n",
        "* The metric used for loss which is the difference between the predicted and actual values is Mean Squared Error\n",
        "* THe metric used used for accuracy is Mean Absolute Error\n",
        "* The model.fit function trains the model. 100 epochs means it trains the model 100 times throught tthe training set and a batch size of 16 is the number of training samples processed in one forward and backward pass through the neural network before the model's parameters are updated\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "background_save": true,
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "3L8YnYg3VE9a",
        "outputId": "20d37356-6d3e-4772-d481-18356329ffc5"
      },
      "outputs": [
        {
          "name": "stderr",
          "output_type": "stream",
          "text": [
            "/usr/local/lib/python3.12/dist-packages/keras/src/layers/rnn/rnn.py:199: UserWarning: Do not pass an `input_shape`/`input_dim` argument to a layer. When using Sequential models, prefer using an `Input(shape)` object as the first layer in the model instead.\n",
            "  super().__init__(**kwargs)\n"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "source": [
        "\n",
        "width = np.shape(X_train)[1]\n",
        "height = np.shape(y_train)[2]\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "LSTM_model = Sequential()\n",
        "LSTM_model.add(LSTM(64, return_sequences=False, input_shape=(width, height)))\n",
        "LSTM_model.add(Dropout(0.3))\n",
        "LSTM_model.add(Dense(look_back))\n",
        "\n",
        "optimizer = Adam(learning_rate=0.01)\n",
        "LSTM_model.compile(loss=MeanSquaredError(), optimizer=optimizer, metrics=['mae'])"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "background_save": true
        },
        "id": "QUht5aLJWrPo"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "history = LSTM_model.fit(X_train, y_train, epochs=100, batch_size=16, verbose=0)\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "EO6jiwlVlNSn"
      },
      "source": [
        "**Model Prediction**\n",
        "* This obtains the predicted values of the trained model"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
